      <title>Pumpkin Spice Hotté</title>
      <author> BrieIsCheese </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1344167/pumpkin-spice-hott/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1344167-pumpkin-spice-hott/chapter/1344169/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">22b4143036649674fabdd54e97d35fca55a7a8b8</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 25 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is a 4807 word long comedic slice of life story about an arranged date at a coffee shop between a transfem egg and trans girl. It takes place in the same urban fantasy setting as my erotica Euphoria Scented Candle (18+), but is safe for work and independent from it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;CW: Implied lactation joke, mentioned online stalking, mentioned arson that's played as a joke, mention of MLM, swearing&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1344167-pumpkin-spice-hott/chapter/1344169/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Pumpkin Spice Hotté&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Going on an arranged date at six AM was far down on my list of things for my ideal Saturday morning, but I'd been single long enough that meeting a friend of a friend's former roommate's ex-coworker seemed preferable to my current weekend plan of doing zero, zip, zilch, followed by a bunch of nada and then finishing Sunday off with a whole lot of nothing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Still, I wasn't desperate enough to meet anywhere but a coffee shop. Even if the date went abhorrently bad, at least I’d have caffeine in me. The things we do for a statistically low chance at love, I suppose. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I had been told she'd be wearing a wicker sun hat with a pink ribbon on it. Maybe the fact the sun was barely out this time of day and it was late Autumn would have weirded out some people, but much like everything else in life I hadn't even registered it as unusual.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As I entered the building the smell of coffee grinds hit me, only slightly tinged with cleaning supplies. A pasty white woman in a black hoodie, black skinny jeans, and forest green apron bearing the logo of the café was languidly wiping the same spot on an already clean table.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Is she a vampire? Why in the world would she be working a shift with the sun out?&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I walked to the counter and waited awkwardly for one of the two employees to notice the other wasn't taking my order. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Honey, can you get his order?” an older woman, presumably the manager, asked the other lady.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Wha?! Oh, yeah,” the woman washing the table said with a start.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I didn't often go out for coffee, since it's expensive as hell for the quality you get and because I don't actually go out often… probably more the latter. However since I was going to be here anyway for the date, I felt obligated to at least buy something.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Good morning! A pumpkin spice latte and a slice of banana bread, please,” I beamed, after the woman finally made it to the counter.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I'd been given shit before about how girly my tastes are, but it's a hot caffeine milkshake that tastes like pumpkin pie. What's not to like? Acting like certain foods are only for one gender is juvenile posturing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Honestly, I don't give a shit about anyone who says or implies traditionally feminine things are worse than traditionally masculine things. Girls are fucking great and have amazing taste in beverages, so I Stan women. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“That'll be nine eighty-four. Your drink will be out in a few minutes.” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Umm, if you don't mind me asking, why are you working the opening shift? Isn't the sun really dangerous for you?” I asked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She briefly gave me a confused look, then she groaned and her voice dropped into a bored monotone that implied she'd explained this hundreds of times. “It's a job, it pays a living wage, it doesn't require prior work experience.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh, right, capitalism… sorry.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My embarrassment at being unintentionally inconsiderate and the barista being rightfully annoyed at me kept my mouth firmly shut. I paid and quickly hurried to a quiet table to wait for my drink and my date.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Morning people are an oppressive class,” I heard her mutter under her breath as I walked away.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I suddenly jolted to attention when the bell on the door rang announcing that someone had entered the store. A stunning cow girl in a yellow blouse, overalls, and a straw sun hat with a pretty pink ribbon tied to it walked in. Her short horns propped up the hat in a very cute way and I suddenly understood why she was wearing it; she just looked that freaking good in it. Her tail swept lazily from side to side as she walked towards me, accentuating her swaying hips.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Holy shit, that can't be my date. She's gorgeous! &lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I realized I was staring slack-jawed at her and quickly made myself stop leering at her so I wouldn’t immediately creep her out. She gave me a little smirk and asked with a touch of a southern drawl, “Jacob?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Y-yeah, that's me. You must be Madeline, then.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Please call me Maddie. No one calls me Madeline unless they're angry at me.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Gotcha, Maddie when I'm not mad.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Cute. Do you mind if I order right quick, then we can get this date started?” she asked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Of course,” I said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She came back after a couple minutes and sat down across from me then asked, “Alrighty, how are you doing?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“A bit nervous, honestly, never gone on an arranged date before. I don't know if I would have even thought of trying one if left to my own devices.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I totally get it. Why bother with going on a date with someone you know nothing about when online dating exists.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Exactly. So what do you do for a living?” I asked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I work in the dairy industry,” the cow girl replied coyly. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The look on my face after hearing that must have been very funny for her to laugh that hard. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I'm a mechanic,” she eventually managed to get out between cackling. “I fix industrial equipment.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh gods, I'm so so sorry. I wasn't-” I began, but was cut off.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No no, I led you into it. It's just a joke I pull sometimes to break the ice.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“More like shattered into a million little pieces,” I chuckled, relieved I hadn't fucked up the date immediately. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Really, no one besides other mechanics find my job interesting, so that joke is about all there is to say about it. So unless you want to hear me complain about how the design of an IDC centrifugal separator makes it a pain in the ass to repair, we should probably talk about something else.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I mean, if you want to talk about something you're passionate about, it doesn't really matter to me what it is.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Really, like you're not just saying that as a first date line?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;”Seriously, I like hearing people nerd out about stuff. I once had a friend give me a two hour presentation about Bionicle lore and I enjoyed every minute of it.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh, cool. I might have to take you up on that sometime. What's your job?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I work in social services, undoing curses for underprivileged people.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Damn, well, you got me beat on the interesting job front.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Honestly, I mostly do the prep work for our field agents. Researching how a curse works and how to counter it is ninety percent of the gig. I spent most of my time nose-deep in musty old books.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“The other ten?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Our department's resources are spread paper thin for the amount of work we do, so in the scenarios that aren't considered dangerous enough for field agents, I or one of the other researchers end up breaking the curses. Of course, there is a tiny margin of error on determining that, so I've been in a couple scrapes, but nothing serious. Worst that's happened is a mage that was previously friendly got upset and knocked me into a wall with wind magic before I could talk them down. Did manage to deescalate and break their curse after that, so happy endings all around.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Wow, that's pretty impressive!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Thanks, I am very proud of that one.“&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Any other cool stories?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“One or two, but I’ve got to tiptoe around any identifying details of cases to protect the victims. I could go on for hours on the process, but let's see… There was this one I still think about a lot. There was this misogynist that pissed off a witch and she cursed him to have to spend a year with a woman's body.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Huh, I figured that kind of thing only happened in obscure trans fic.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Right?!” I said, a bit over-enthusiastically that someone else had been down the research rabbit hole I'd gone into while looking into the curse. “Umm, anyway, we looked for the witch for weeks and came up with nothing. None of the rituals or restoration magic we tried worked. Eventually I had to painstakingly design a transformation spell to turn him back into his old self manually. But here's the kicker, when I presented the spell to him &lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;she&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt; informed me that she didn't want to go back to her old body.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“How thoroughly unpredictable,” Maddie commented dryly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Exactly what I said, but who could blame her for wanting to stay a woman?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Maddie gave me a curious look and nodded silently in agreement. I continued the story.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Since the victim didn't want to be freed from the curse anymore, the case was officially shut. Legally speaking there was nothing more we could do to help her, but I later heard she'd convinced a very kind and talented cursebreaker to make it permanent under the table.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My heart skipped a beat when I realized how carried away I'd gotten in telling the story and how I had basically admitted to skirting around the law to someone I'd just met. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“That was really cool of whoever that mysterious person was to take such a huge risk to help a girl out,” Maddie grinned, then added in a hushed tone, “Don't worry I won't rat you out for being a compassionate person. The world would be a better place if more people were like you.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“T-thanks.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Our conversation continued on like that for some time. It didn't take long for me to become completely smitten with her charm, confidence, and compassion. She was such a wildly perfect match for me that at one point I literally pinched myself to make sure I wasn't dreaming, making it all the more jarring when after another hour of chatting she asked something of me out of nowhere. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Alright, what's your game?” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Huh?” I gawked. “I'd thought the date was going extraordinarily well so far.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“That's exactly the problem.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What are you talking about?” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I made a deal with a fae named Oona to find my soulmate. She said I had to go on one hundred dates before finding them and each one has gone progressively worse than the last. During my last date we went for ice cream and a freak blizzard hit; we were snowed in the building for hours. The whole nine hours we were trapped in there my date tried to get me to invest in an AI company, an MLM, and Arby's. Just as someone finished shoveling out the snow from the door the building caught fire.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I just stared at her blankly; I had no idea how to even begin to respond to that. Instead I nervously sipped at my coffee. Certainly I had many things I could say, after all, dealing with this kind of thing was my job. I could talk about how deals with the fae were fairly rare both because very few of them bother with individual mortals anymore and because of the Faustian reputation those that do have. Or I could mention the most reliable way to get out of a bargain with one was to offer them something they wanted even more than what you’d given them to begin with. However, in the context of a first date with a woman I really liked, I was stumped for words.  &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No one was hurt in the fire,” Maddie added eventually.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Uhh, good to hear.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Like, you're a guy and I'm a lesbian so there's that, but nothing abnormal has happened. As far as I can tell you're just a genuinely nice person who would be a really good match if…” She trailed off, now deep in thought. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;At least she isn't expecting me to respond while she's thinking whatever this is through, &lt;/i&gt;I thought to myself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Awkward silences are my natural habitat; if any given conversation I'm in goes on long enough, I'll be whisked away into the horrible quiet; I'll feel obliged to stop and inevitably start overthinking an acceptable way to do it. The longer it’s been since someone spoke the more pressure to break the silence and the more my mind decides I have to say something ‘good’ enough or people will suddenly hate me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This left me to try and dissect all that info for literally anything to say. Clearly I couldn't go right into the fact she's gay, it would be rude. Still, I had to say something and picked the only thing I felt qualified to talk about.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“So a deal with a fae?” I said, then cringed at how boring and forced that felt to say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah, she said something like ‘After you commit to one hundred arranged dates, you will find your true love.’ Sorry, I realize I'm dropping a lot on you and the hell I've been through the past few months is in no way your fault. Looks like I'm the one fucking this one up,” she joked meekly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Apology accepted, umm, you want to call it, then? I had no idea you're gay. Kinda moot point to continue the date.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We could just hang out for a while longer, if you want. I was having a lot of fun just chatting with you.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Same; honestly, I’m wishing I were a girl so we could still date… Not that I'm going to try and convince you to try anyway as some homophobic ‘you haven't had the right dick’ bullshit. Just saying we seem like we'd be a really good match if we weren't incompatible.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Wait, what?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What do you mean what?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What you just said.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We'd be a good match if you weren't gay?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No, what you said before that.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Uhh, the thing about not having the right dick?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No, the first sentence you said.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah, that's me. You must be Madeline then?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh my god…” She facepalmed, but I could see through her fingers she was trying very hard not to laugh. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;After she regained her composure she opened her mouth to speak, but was interrupted by the barista who was suddenly at our table with two drinks.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Someone canceled their take-out order. Would you two like some free coffee?” she asked with a slight smirk.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“That sounds great, thank you,” Maddie said, still fixated on me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Y-yeah, thanks,” I said with a start.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Maddie waited for the barista to go away to continue. “You said you wished you were a girl.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah, so? Girls are cool,” I said, only slightly defensively.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Maddie looked blankly at me for a moment, then her eyes drifted away, deep in thought.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You're doing your ‘protagonist having a dramatic internal monologue’ face again,” I commented. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There was a second she just stared at me in disbelief, then she burst out in laughter. I couldn't help but to join in, her laugh just had something about it that filled me with infectious joy. Our laughter eventually died down, much to the relief of the barista, who had been glaring at us.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“So what's up?” I asked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Uhh, well… okay, let me think of how to phrase this. There's some… things I want to ask you. They might be on the personal side, and if it makes you uncomfortable let me know and I'll drop it, no questions asked. The thing is it could end up being nothing, but it could end up changing your life for the better. Are you okay with this?” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I can hardly say no after that preamble. What's this about?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Promise me you'll tell me to stop if you're uncomfortable talking about it.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah, of course,” I agreed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Okay, how much do you know about transgender stuff?” she asked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;What an odd and completely out of the blue question. What possible reason would she ask me this?&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Not much, I guess? I've been told I live under a rock, but I assure you I crawl out often enough to not be a bigot if that's what you're asking. They can live their lives however they want as far as I'm concerned, but what does it have to do with anything?” I asked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh, right, I guess I hadn't told you yet. I'm a trans woman, but that's not why I asked.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;At that moment I started to take my first sip of my new coffee and immediately regretted it. It was still scalding hot and I had to force down my mouthful of lava so to not do a spit-take right after that admission.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Ahur twansjinder? Dat's o cool,” I managed to say with my tongue still burning.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Coffee a bit hot?” she asked while clearly trying to hide her amusement. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Mahbe.” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You're okay though, right?” she asked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Ool be fvine,” I confirmed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I guess I'll just come out with it. Have you ever considered what it'd be like to be a girl?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah, but everyone does that on occasion. What would it be like if I were born the opposite sex?” I said. I noted I felt oddly compelled to defend myself, even though there was nothing to defend against.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“How often would you say you do that?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Three to four times a week, but like I said, no more than anyone else.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Right… have you ever considered whether or not that'd be something you'd actually like?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No, I haven't,” I replied slowly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Believe it or not, I actually hadn't; it had always just been a fun idea for me to think about to occupy my time. Until now I'd never given it a second thought. Throwing my daydream fodder into the spotlight felt… not uncomfortable per se, but very strange, like moving a muscle you didn't know you had. With that and how pointed her questions were, she was obviously getting at something important, and I wasn't sure I liked where this was going. Even still, there was a crushing feeling of inevitability hovering over me and felt compelled to see this through. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Are you still good? Should I shut up?” she asked, concerned.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I'm good, keep going,” I nodded.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Alright, so this is the ninety-fifth date out of a hundred, but I'd wanted to get this over with, so I scheduled the last five for all the same day.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I don't get your point.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“So I've already committed to a hundred arranged dates.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh,” I said. “So you could meet your soulmate anytime now.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Depends on how the fae I made the deal with, Oona, thinks, but yeah.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And you're gay… and trans,” I said slowly, my confusion starting to turn into panic.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She watched me intently, waiting for me to come to my own conclusions.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Presumably your soulmate could be trans too, and we'd be a really good match if I were–” My voice broke mid-sentence. After a second I recovered and continued in a reverent whisper, “It's me… isn't it?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Could be; I'd like to hang out with you more, if nothing else.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“That would be nice.” I smiled softly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hey, umm, I hope this isn't too weird, but do you want a hug?” Maddie offered.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I nodded; she got up and sat back down next to me and wrapped her arms around me. She was just the right level of warm and softer than silk. Reveling in her embrace was easy, it simply felt right, like I belonged there with her.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You're so comfy,” I mumbled almost unconsciously. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Likewise, cutie.” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Maddie?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I think I might be a girl.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“That would make you the cutest girl I've ever met,” she grinned. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;While I wasn't the most versed in trans matters there was no mistaking the incredible wave of joy that fell over me at being called a girl for the first time. I just had a taste of gender euphoria and longed for more of that wonderful sensation.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I never thought I could be this happy,” I sighed, with a tear in my eye.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“This is just the beginning, think of all the outfits you'll get to try and what effects hormones could have on you.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I made a very feminine noise of excitement. As eager as I was to go do all that and more I was quite enjoying just being in Maddie's arms. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Zoey is a nice name,” I murmured after a while.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You want to be my Zoey?” she asked, petting my head lightly as she talked. It felt almost supernaturally pleasant and I could feel a lovely warm sensation overcoming me. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Y-yeah, I think I'd like that.” We stayed like that for a few moments before I asked in almost a moan, “Gods, since when does getting your head rubbed feel this good?” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“In my experience it always has, but, umm, maybe we should give it a rest for now, we are still in public.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I sat bolt upright, realizing how intimate things were getting. The café was getting fairly crowded at this point but thankfully everyone else was too busy with their own lives to pay any mind to us.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“R-right.” I glanced at my phone to check the time. “Gods, how is it all seven o'clock? Finding my soulmate and realizing I'm a woman only took two hours?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Time flies when you're having your life changed,” Maddie shrugged. “Just be glad you were spared the nearly a hundred shitty dates.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah, seriously that must’ve sucked ass. That reminds me, I'd wanted to ask you something about that. You said you had to commit to a hundred dates, right?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah, so?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Technically speaking, you just had to commit to the dates, right? Couldn't you have just scheduled them and just canceled before you actually had to go on them?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What…? Oh gods dammit.” Maddie buried her face in her hands and groaned loudly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“There is much to be said for careful crafted phrasing to close all loopholes, but personally I like seeing if the mark will even notice them at all,” the barista mused, suddenly back at our table. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The pale woman snapped her fingers and Maddie turned to her with a look of recognition like she'd just truly noticed her. Some kind of magic that had veiled her identity, I guessed; the fae were well known for their mastery of illusions of all sorts. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And you got what was promised, didn't you?” she smirked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You! What are you doing here?” Maddie spat.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“One can hardly expect me to go through so much effort to help with your love life without me wanting to see the ending.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Wait, you're the fae that cursed her? I thought you were a vampire!” I blurted out.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Your assumption is rather flawed, silly girl. Just because someone is pale, wearing all black, and hiding from the sun does not mean they are a vampire. I am just a night owl and appreciate goth fashion,” Oona explained.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“That's… fucking fair, I guess. Shame on me for being reductive,” I conceded. “Why did you go along with it?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It was funny to watch you squirm,” she smirked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Can we get back to the part where this woman made my life hell the last few months?” Maddie asked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Made your life hell? I have been particularly generous considering the magnitude of the service I provided you. I promised you that you would ‘be with your true love.’ It is by my kindness alone that I choose not to interpret that differently. Our bargain could have concluded with you two buried in the same grave and I'd still have been true to my word.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;If there was any doubt in my mind of the wisdom of the phrase ‘never strike a deal with a fae’ it vanished as my blood ran cold. I looked at the coffee cup I'd been drinking out of in dread. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I have not tampered with your drinks, nor do I plan to harm either of you. I merely wished to point out the carelessness of your phrasing,” she promised.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Fine, fine. What about all the crap that happened during the other dates I went on?” Maddie asked, clearly fed up with all of this.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You provided a couple months of quality entertainment for me and I made sure you met the girl of your dreams. I quite think the deal was well in your favor, but I rather like happy endings.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You knew I'm a girl?” I asked incredulously.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The fae woman looked at me and raised a perfectly sculpted eyebrow. “Do I really need to dignify that question with an answer?” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;When I continued to stare sternly at her, she rolled her eyes, then made a gesture with one hand and a piece of paper appeared out of nowhere. She began to read a list of familiar internet search terms.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Annoying a witch to make them curse you, how to get cursed to be a girl, cursed to get to be a girl, free spells to make someone a girl, cursed video to make me a girl, real cursed video to make me a girl, Fallout: New Vegas 2… need I go on?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“New Vegas 2 really? The only way that's going to happen is if it's a shit cash grab with very few of the original team behind it,” Maddie said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It could happen,” I mumbled. “H-how did you get that anyway?!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Finding someone's soulmate used to be an involved process; I would often have to take months or years of delicate care to cast such a finely tailored spell to find the single being among all others whose soul was meant to be with my target  and that was only for couples. Imagine trying to do the same for when more than two souls are entwined; utterly tedious.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I can imagine,” I grumbled, not happy she was ignoring my question. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Modern technology simplified things ever so much by tracking your every whim and habit, reducing them to easily accessible data. I can narrow it down to a few dozen people in a week, then manually check your soul's compatibility.  Given all parties are as terminally online as you two.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hey, I don't spend &lt;i&gt;that&lt;/i&gt; much time on the computer!” Maddie objected.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Do you even believe that or are you just saying that to keep up appearances in front of your date?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I – You're enjoying this, aren't you? You're trying your damnedest to annoy and fluster us. Is all this just a game to you?” Maddie growled.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Oona laughed at her like a queen at her court jester saying something particularly foolish. “Of course, dear. I don't do all this solely out of the kindness of my heart.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You're a real piece of work,” Maddie scowled.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh, lighten up. You have the rest of your life together with your soulmate. Certainly that's worth some light mischief to you?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You burnt down a building!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Did I? I heard tell that the owner had been stealing tips from his staff for nearly a decade. Maybe one of his employees simply got fed up with him?” she said, a devilish smile playing across her face.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“So fucking what, me and a few others were still in the building!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You exaggerate; everyone who was there was leaving just as the fire started.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Well… yeah, but still it was scary.” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Fire often is,” the fae said dismissively. “Now if you are quite done complaining about my hobbies, I must take my leave, but first…” she turned to me, “I would like to offer you a deal. I will warn you it will come at a high price.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;While I knew the risks of actually accepting a deal with a fae, Oona had proven to me she was more benevolent than most. Clearly dangerous and more than a little mischievous, but I didn't think she would intentionally hurt us. Plus I was very curious what her offer would be.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Might as well hear her out,” I shrugged.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Are you serious, after what she put me through?!” Maddie hissed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Oona continued as if she didn't hear Maddie. “You see, my wife is a talented alchemist and has devoted much of her life to curing a particular malady, body dysphoria and dysmorphia. I will give you a vial of my wife's magnum opus, Euphoria. This particular version will immediately and permanently transform your body to the one you most want and in return you give me… two hundred dollars.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What?” Maddie and I asked in synced disbelief.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“A high price indeed.” Oona nodded gravely, but a playful smile gave away how seriously she was actually taking this. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My years of expertise in dealing with curses warned me this could be a trick and I could very well damn myself if I took the bait. Despite the very real danger involved with dealing with the fae, my newfound need to fix my body begged me to agree to it. I came up with the only response I could possibly give.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Do you take credit?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
